<p><ent>Thrid</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Thrid
<hw>Thrid</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Thridded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Thridding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[A variant of
<ets>thread</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pass through in the manner
of a thread or a needle; to make or find a course through; to
thread.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some <qex>thrid</qex> the mazy ringlets of her hair.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And now he <qex>thrids</qex> the bramble bush.</q> <rj><qau>J. R.
Drake.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I began⟦br⟧
To <qex>thrid</qex> the musky-circled mazes.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make or effect (a way or course) through
something; <as>as, to <ex>thrid</ex> one's way through a
wood</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thrid</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Thrid
<hw>Thrid</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Thread; continuous line.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I resume the <qex>thrid</qex> of my discourse.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thrifallow</ent>⟦br⟧
